<font color="#FF0000">A CORPSMAN STORY..</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 18 22:13:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Back in January of this year, Mr Bozyk suggested this forum, <br>
and Mr. Varanelli asked if any corpsmen would be willing to <br>
participate.  Since then there seem to have been two additions<br>
to the topic.  Not a large response!  Perhaps those corpsmen<br>
who have seen this dialogue feel as I did (and sometimes<br>
still do); that our memories of those experiences overwhelm <br>
us - that they cannot be shared in any real sense.<br><br>
I was a corpsman working in an intensive care unit of a MASH<br>
Hospital in the Delta.  I was there one year.  That year<br>
was the watershed of my life (and, I sure that is not an<br>
orginal observation).  As so many others did, I stuffed all<br>
those emotions and memories for many years; heck I even<br>
became an intensive care nurse with I got back!  However,<br>
I was fortuately able to receive PTSD counseling.  I have<br>
found in the years since, that the best way to express what<br>
VietNam was for me is through writing.  So, I would like to<br>
share a story which represents not only what VietNam was<br>
like for me, but also the struggles I have gone through<br>
since, as a veteran working as a nurse.  I just hope the<br>
story means something whoever is interested.<br><br>
 <br>
GAUZEMAN <br>
 <br>
The shell-- <br>
 <br>
 From the Vietnamese dawn’s fading stars, sweat, and stillness, <br>
 Into the buzzing fluorescent glare of the ward, <br>
 Steps the experienced corpsman, <br>
 Indrawn, and cool. <br>
 He stands, detached, competent, able, <br>
 Purple Heart in his footlocker, and now <br>
 Less than thirty days to go. <br>
 <br>
 He yawns, fatigued, waiting for his patient assignments <br>
 To begin one more, and one less, <br>
 Damned day-shift. <br>
 He snuffs out his after-chow cigarette, saving the butt, <br>
 And warily glances toward the two new nurses, <br>
 So precise and pink, and innocent. <br>
 They patter and plan while <br>
 The new corpsmen look to him, <br>
 And feign confidence. <br>
 <br>
 He sighs, and slowly shakes his head, knowing how soon, <br>
 And how drastically, <br>
 They all will be forced to change. <br>
 It will be a practical matter of surviving-- <br>
 Surviving half-assed sane.  <br>
 <br>
 <br>
The dread-- <br>
 <br>
 He casually looks over the unit, <br>
 Counting, and noting any new ones. <br>
 Last bed on the left, that’s a new one. <br>
 The doc’s still with him, so he’s fresh in from surgery. <br>
 A twinge of gut tightening, as <br>
 He sights in, and looks more carefully. <br>
 <br>
 The body in that bed is wrapped completely in white gauze, <br>
 Just the eyes, nose and lips show. <br>
 The right foot is gone. <br>
 His practiced eyes note small spots of fresh blood  <br>
 Painting the gauze cocoon. <br>
 The sight spears his carefully hardened brain, <br>
 (To prick and prod him with detail for years.) <br>
 <br>
 &quot;Damn!&quot; he softly says, as he feels that familiar dread begin. <br>
 The stomach sinking, aching, and puking kind of <br>
 Dread.  Thus, he knows the <br>
 Gauzed man is his patient this day. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
The play-- <br>
 <br>
 Unknowingly, pink nurses confirm this duty. <br>
 The corpsman slowly walks toward that far left bed, <br>
 And the doctor, O’Rourke. <br>
 The two had daily worked together for almost a year. <br>
 O’Rourke had come running through sporadic mortars <br>
 When the corpsman was wounded back during TET. <br>
 But, today appears routine; <br>
 Another performance of the long-running play. <br>
 But, the dread tells the corpsman that today will be special. <br>
 It shouts from his gut. <br>
 <br>
 The doc says in a quiet, tired way, <br>
 &quot;Take care of this man.&quot; <br>
 The medic nods, and mumbles to himself, <br>
 &quot;Hell, Doc, you know me. <br>
 You know I will.&quot; <br>
 Then the corpsman <br>
 Stops.  This is not the usual script. <br>
 He looks at O’Rourke for a cue, and sees it in his face, <br>
 In his gray-blue eyes. <br>
 Those eyes waver, and turn away, and face muscles flex. <br>
 It’s clear now, the gut was right. <br>
 This gauze-man is going to die. <br>
 <br>
  <br>
The connection-- <br>
 <br>
 The corpsman’s lips compress.  His thoughts explode, <br>
 &quot;Oh Shit, not again!  Goddamn it! Why can’t a fucking <br>
 New guy do this! <br>
 I’ve already done my damned share!&quot; <br>
 <br>
 How many times before? <br>
 He’d long since been forced not to count. <br>
 Turning back toward surgery, O’Rourke says, <br>
 &quot;Give him blood.  Try to keep the damned blood pressure up. <br>
 Maybe the bleeding will slow down,  <br>
 But it hasn’t yet.  What fucking fucked-up mess. <br>
 Damn, I’d give anything for a drink.&quot; <br>
 <br>
 Abandoned and pissed, the corpsman turns to <br>
 The red splotched gauze-man. <br>
 &quot;Shit, man, just you and me.&quot; <br>
 <br>
 By habit, and long practice, <br>
 He quickly checks the blood pressure and pulse, <br>
 And then, <br>
 Pauses a moment to look. <br>
 (For years to come, he would wonder why lessons <br>
 Dearly learned, abandoned him at that moment.) <br>
 The gauze-man’s face is mostly covered, <br>
 But the corpsman can see small <br>
 Holes and cuts around the eyes and on the lips. <br>
 He senses this man is older than the usual here, <br>
 More his own age. <br>
 And then it happens, like lightening from a blue sky <br>
 To earth, he connects with Gauzeman. <br>
 He’d brakes the survival rule. <br>
 It is now personal. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
The obsession-- <br>
 <br>
 Suddenly, the corpsman is inside a filmy sphere. <br>
 The rest of the world goes fuzzy and distant. <br>
 There are only the corpsman and Gauzeman <br>
 In the focused part. <br>
 A white, red spotted, mummy tended <br>
 By a young-old, jungle-fatigued conrade. <br>
 It seems quiet inside that sphere, <br>
 Just the breathing of the two, <br>
 And the mumbled words of the corpsman. <br>
 &quot;Man you’re not going to die! <br>
 I can’t let that happen, again.&quot; <br><br>
 Time in the sphere doesn’t run straight, <br>
 But zigzags, advances and then halts, then surges again. <br>
 The corpsman works feverishly, then pauses, <br>
 To look and assess. <br>
 Blood becomes the enemy advancing across the field of gauze. <br>
 &quot;Hey, Man, stop bleeding!  I can pump this blood in <br>
 Only so fast.  Work with me, Man!&quot; <br>
 <br>
 Another pause, and a pool of blood has appeared <br>
 Surrounding Gauzeman. <br>
 Dazed, the corpsman whisper screams, <br>
 &quot;Have to work faster.  Get the blood in you. <br>
 Man, I don’t know what else to do.&quot; <br>
 He’s not sure he even said it aloud. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
The joke-- <br>
 <br>
 &quot;I can do it, shit Man, we can do it! <br>
 You’re not dying!  Too many have.  I just can’t, <br>
 Fucking can’t, watch another one die!&quot; <br>
 Gauzeman mute, keeps bleeding, <br>
 The blood pool deepens. <br>
 Frenzied desperation overwhelm the corpsman. <br>
 His practiced numb detachment is overrun. <br>
 He quietly rages, runs for more blood bags, <br>
 And pumps them in fast.  Gauzeman floats in blood, <br>
 A deep pool reflecting fluorescent light with <br>
 A dark sticky metallic sheen. <br>
 <br>
 The corpsman slips and almost falls.  Time pauses <br>
 Once more.  &quot;Why the hell, is the floor slick?&quot; <br>
 Then he sees that Gauzeman’s blood <br>
 Mocks him by dripping off the mattress edge <br>
 Splattering the floor.  Bight red speckles in <br>
 A laughter pattern, giggles appearing <br>
 Here and there, at random. <br>
 The unholy bloody Random God has <br>
 Chosen Gauzeman and the corpsman <br>
 For his day’s amusement. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
The death-- <br>
 <br>
 O’Rourke appears out of the mist, <br>
 Saying nothing.  The corpsman smiles, <br>
 And almost laughs.  O’Rourke steps carefully onto the blood, <br>
 The giggles quiet.  He glances at Gauzeman, <br>
 Then focuses on the pile of empty <br>
 Blood bags.  He takes a slow deep breath, and <br>
 Sighs it out, &quot;Jeezzz.&quot; <br>
 Then  without turning, he mumbles, <br>
 &quot;Just go outside, now.&quot; <br>
 O’Rourke, the corpsman knows, will <br>
 Let Gauzeman die.  &quot;You said take care of him.&quot; <br>
 <br>
 &quot;Just go outside.  I’ll find you later.  We’ll get drunk, <br>
 And talk about what ‘take care’ means to us.&quot; <br>
 The corpsman shrugs, <br>
 &quot;Hell if I know anymore.  Do you? <br>
 When does caring mean you quit trying? <br>
 Why are we here?&quot; <br>
 He turns and walks out on stilt-numb legs. <br>
 Shaking his head, he chuckles, <br>
 And listens to the blood laugh good-bye. <br>
 Puzzled and abandoned, the new corpsmen <br>
 Watch him go. <br>
 <br>
 <br>
The love-- <br>
 <br>
 Outside, mid afternoon heat and light blast his face. <br>
 &quot;God help me, I love <br>
 This place.&quot;<br>

